As a frontend engineer myself, I spent years trying to learn how to build smooth, performant, and resilient web applications. I mostly work with React, trying to fine tune state management and optimize build pipelines, but today I’m going to do the opposite.
I’m going to write how to completely wreck a web application!
But why? Last year I was working on a very large project which had more than 500 features, but the software (web application) was very laggy and it was leaking memory in almost every place, as the development timeline was very tight, many parts of the code were written in a hurry. As a mid level developer I fixed some memory leaks and I thought I did a great job. It solved some issues, but the application was still laggy. At that time I never thought about event loop. As I was studying about the event loop recently, I found out some of the issues that the software had were actually coming from the event loop. From an engineer’s perspective, the code that causes a site to crash, stutter or drop to zero frames per second isn’t a random thing, it is the logical result of exploiting the JavaScript engine’s core architecture.
What is Our Goal?
Our goal is very simple: make the web page feel incredibly heavy, laggy, broken and trigger “Page Unresponsive” pop-up.
Let’s start our digital destruction.
The JavaScript Engine’s Weak Point
JavaScript Event LoopBefore we start breaking things, we need to understand the browser architecture we are targeting. JavaScript is single treaded. It can do one thing at a time. The browser coordinates this single thread using 3 main pillars.

• The Call Stack: Where synchronous JavaScript code actually runs.

• Web APIs/Background Tasks: Where asynchronous operations like network request, DOM events and timers stay while waiting for their turn to be executed.

• The Task Queues: Where completed async tasks wait to be pushed back on to the stack.
The event loop has one simple, relentless job: look at the call stack, if the call stack is empty, take the first item from the queue and push it onto the stack.
If I can keep that call stack permanently occupied, the event loop goes on strike, the browser stops rendering updates, and the user gets the famous “Page Unresponsive” dialog. Let’s make it happen.
Level 1: Synchronous Call Stack Blocking
If the call stack never drains to zero, the event loop can never check the queues, and the browser can never paint a single new pixel to the screen. This is the most basic approach.
Infinite Loop
function killBrowser() {
while (true) {
// The stack never empties
}
}Why does it break the site?
This is a pure brute force method. The while loop runs entirely synchronously on the main thread. Because the loop never finishes, the execution context stays glued to the call stack. If the browser runs 60fps, that means the browser’s rendering engine needs to repaint every 16.6ms to maintain a smooth user experience. Here that rendering engine is completely locked out. So the page immediately freezes. Clicks, scrolls and animations all die instantly.
Heavy Math Trap
If we give the stack too much synchronous work to do, it can cause a similar effect like an infinite loop.
// A horribly inefficient Fibonacci calculator
function fibonacci(n) {
if (n < 2) return n;
return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
}
// Block the main thread for several seconds
fibonacci(45);As it will block the main thread for several seconds, the page will be unresponsive for a while.
Any time we parse a massive JSON string using JSON.parse(), or manipulate huge image datasets in memory, or run deep recursive math directly on the main thread, we are building a temporary version of this trap. If we offload these computations to a web worker, running them on a completely separate OS thread, we might overcome the issues.
The Trojan Horse
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Photo by Zeki Okur on UnsplashSuppose you want to trigger a button click. You might think button clicks are user events, they go through the task queue asynchronously. So clicking button.click() programmatically is safe.
But you are wrong! Actually, it is a Trojan horse.
const button = document.querySelector('#destroy-btn');button.addEventListener('click', () => {
console.log('Triggered!');
button.click(); // Synchronous self destruction
});
The moment you run this code, the browser tab crashes.
But why physical human clicks are safe but button.click() is deadly? To understand why this happens, we have to look at how browsers manage task distribution.
When human clicks a button, the click event is handled asynchronously:

• The browser’s native subsystem detects the hardware click.

• It wraps the event and registers onClick in the callback queue (aka task queue).

• The event loop waits for the call stack to be empty, pulls the onClick handler, runs it, and then yields control back to let the browser repaint.

• Even if a user clicks 100 times, the browser handles them one by one, emptying the stack and rendering the page between.
However, when you run button.click() programmatically:

• Javascript bypasses the callback queue entirely.

• It fires the event synchronously, forcing the engine to pause whatever script is currently running on the call stack and execute the click handler immediately.

• Because the recursive .click() runs directly on the stack without yielding to the event loop, the stack rapidly grows until you hit a stack overflow (RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded), or the browser simply freezes.
Programmatic DOM triggers like .click(), .focus(), or custom dispatchEvent() run synchronously. We have to treat them as heavy synchronous functions, not friendly async events. If we need to trigger them safely, we have to push them to the back of the queue by wrapping them in zero-delay timer:
setTimeout(() => button.click(), 0)Level 2: Microtask Starvation
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Photo by Nick Fewings on UnsplashThis is a silent killer. We always think asynchronous is safe, it won’t block the stack synchronously. We expect asynchronous code to run quietly in the background.
function silentDeath() {
Promise.resolve().then(silentDeath);
}
silentDeath();Here the code looks fully asynchronous. There is no infinite loop. Yet, the moment this code executes, the browser tab instantly freezes. Let’s learn the loophole.
The Microtask Loophole
To understand this, we have to look at the hidden hierarchy of the event loop. The loop doesn’t treat all asynchronous queues equally. It divides them into 2 main categories:

• Macrotasks (or just Tasks): setTimeout, setInterval, setImmediate, and I/O events.

• Microtask: Promise.then callbacks, async/await continuations, and queueMicortask().
The rule of event loop is strict: the engine must completely drain the microtask queue before it moves to anything else. If a microtask schedules another microtask, that new microtask is added to the end of the current queue and executed during the current tick of the loop.
[Call Stack Empties]
│
▼
[Process ALL Microtasks] ◄─── If a microtask adds another microtask,
│ the loop stays here forever!
▼
[Render / Paint Screen]
│
▼
[Process ONE Macrotask]Now look at our silentDeath function, it recursively adds another Promise callback to the microtask queue before the current one finishes, the queue length never reaches zero. The event loop is trapped in a microtask vortex. It can never yield to the rendering engine, and the page dies silently without even throwing a syntax error.
Level 3: Macrotask Flooding
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Photo by Kelly Sikkema on UnsplashWe can call it death by a thousand cuts. What happens if we try the same recursive trick like the previous one, but swap the microstack for a macrotask?
function floodTasks() {
setTimeout(floodTasks, 0);
}
floodTasks();The result is that the website doesn’t crash! We can still click buttons, scroll and see text animations.
Why is Macrotask Play Nice?
The event loop handles macrotask differently. It only processes 1 macrotask from the queue per tick, then yields control back to see if the browser needs to perform a layout or repaint phase, before moving on to the next task. Furthermore, browsers modernly clamp nested setTimeout calls to a minimum delay of 4ms to protect system resources.
How to Actually Break it with Macrotask
If a single setTimeout won’t kill the page, we just need to scale our attack vector. Instead of a single chain, we generate thousands of them simultaneously.
// Flood the queue with tens of thousands of individual tasks
function absoluteChaos() {
for (let i = 0; i < 50000; i++) {
setTimeout(() => {
// Do minor DOM manipulation or lookups here
document.body.setAttribute('data-tick', Math.random());
}, 0);
}
}While this might not instantly trigger the “Page Unresponsive” pop-up, it causes massive UI jank. Because the macrotask queue is flooded with tens of thousands of minor callbacks, the time between the browsers’ render ticks stretches out. Frames drop from 60fps to single digits. The page feels incredibly heavy, laggy, and broken to the user.
Level 4: Layout Thrashing
We can call it the hardware torture. We don’t always need JavaScript queues to ruin a user’s experience. We can break the interaction between JavaScript engine and browser’s rendering pipeline. The browser executes a very specific pipeline when it draws a frame:
JavaScript -> Style -> Layout -> Paint -> CompositeNormally, the browser waits until the end of our script execution, batches all DOM changes together, and runs a single layout and paint phase. But we can force it to run that heavy geometry calculation dozens of times in a fraction of a second.
// How to drop our frame rate to zero instantly
function tortureLayout() {
const boxes = document.querySelectorAll('.box'); for (let i = 0; i < boxes.length; i++) {
// Write a style change
boxes[i].style.width = (boxes[i].offsetWidth + 10) + 'px';
}
}
The Mechanism of Layout Thrashing
Look closely at the loop:

• We modify the style property of the box. This marks the layout of the page as “dirty”.

• In the very next iteration of the loop, we ask for a geometric property offsetWidth.
Because the style was just dirtied, the browser can’t give us an accurate answer for offsetWidth without knowing the exact new layout. It is forced to immediately pause our JavaScript execution, perform a costly synchronous layout recalculation, return the value and resume the loop.
If we have 500 elements on a page, this loop forces the browser to recalculate the positions and dimensions of every element on the page 500 times in a row, all within a single frame.
Diagnose the Code
Writing bad code is easy, but spotting them is pretty tricky. But we have a few options in our hands.

• Chrome DevTools: Open the performance tab, the press record button, and interact with the target page. Look at red bars labeled “Long task”, any task taking longer than 50ms is actively blocking the main thread and threatening user interactivity.

• The PerformanceObserver API: We can track main thread blocking programmatically in our production monitoring tools to catch layout thrashing and macrotask, microtask bottlenecks.
Conclusion
To write exceptionally resilient code, we have to know precisely where the boundaries of our runtime environment are. We must never block the stack synchronously. Be highly cautious of recursive promise patterns that can lead to microtask starvation. In the browser world “Read before you write” is the golden rule of DOM performance. It means we should always perform all our DOM measurements first, batch them together and only then perform DOM modifications. So now you know exactly how to break a website using JavaScript. Hope you liked the long blog.
